sts would land at roughly 0.5s intervals, which could push slightly above 2 QPS depending on how quickly curl executes. Maybe I should test with `limit-burst-multiplier: 0` to see if nginx handles that case specially and enforces stricter rate limiting. requests arriving every 0.5s means the actual rate is 2 RPS, not 2.22 — I was conflating the time span with the inter-request interval, which are different ways of measuring the same thing.\n\nNow I'm looking at how ingress-nginx implements the burst multiplier. The code shows it defaults to 5 and can be configured, with a minimum burst of 1. If I set the burst multiplier to 0, it would clamp to 1, so that won't help reduce the burst window.\n\nLet me trace through what happens with a rate of 2 RPS and burst of 1 when requests arrive at exactly the rate limit interval. At each 0.5-second mark, the excess tokens decay back to 0, allowing the next request through. This means all requests would pass regardless of the rate limit, which suggests the issue might be something else entirely.\n\nLooking at the problem more carefully, I think the test firing 10 requests with 0.5s sleep between them is meant to be the burst scenario, and the actual rate limit should be configured lower than 2 QPS to force throttling. The task description saying \"limit to 2 QPS\" might mean something different in nginx terms when accounting for burst behavior.\n\nLet me test two approaches: first, setting the rate to 2 with no burst allows everything through at exactly 2 QPS, which doesn't work. Second, dropping the rate to 1 QPS with a default burst of 5 would allow the first 5 requests through immediately, then throttle the remaining 5 since we're sending at 2 QPS but only 1 per second is allowed after the burst. At t=4.5 the burst limit is exceeded and the request gets rejected, so with this configuration I'm getting 9 allowed and 1 rejected. Now testing Approach C with a burst multiplier of 1, which means no actual burst capacity—the rate a